{"title_page": "PlanetMath", "text_new": "{{Infobox website\n| name             = PlanetMath\n| logo             = pmlogo.png\n| logo_size        = 182px\n| screenshot       =\n| caption          =\n| url              = {{URL|http://planetmath.org/}}\n| commercial       = No\n| owner            = PlanetMath.org, Ltd.\n| content_license  = [[CC-BY-SA]]\n| type             = [[Internet encyclopedia project]]\n| language         = [[English language|English]]\n| registration     = [[GitHub]] account required to edit sources via pull request\n| author           = Nathan Egge, Aaron Krowne\n| launch_date      =\n| current_status   = Inactive\n| revenue          =\n| alexa            = 320,431 ({{as of|2019|9|24|alt=September 2019}})<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web|url= https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/planetmath.org|title= Planetmath.org Site Info|publisher= [[Alexa Internet]]|accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n'''PlanetMath''' is a [[free content|free]], collaborative, online [[mathematics]] [[encyclopedia]].  The emphasis is on rigour, openness, [[pedagogy]], real-time content, interlinked content, and also  [[community]] of about 24,000 people with various maths interests. Intended to be comprehensive, the project is currently hosted by the [[University of Waterloo]]. The site is owned by a US-based nonprofit corporation, \"PlanetMath.org, Ltd\".<ref>Self-descriptions of PM {{cite web |url=http://planetmath.org/?op%3Dgetobj%26from%3Dcollab%26id%3D35#SECTION00021000000000000000 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-05-15 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826090901/http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj&from=collab&id=35 |archivedate=2016-08-26 }}, {{cite web |url=http://planetmath.org/?op%3Dabout |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-05-02 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611023918/http://planetmath.org/?op=about |archivedate=2016-06-11 }} {{cite web |url=http://aux.planetmath.org/doc/donate.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-05-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509123133/http://aux.planetmath.org/doc/donate.html |archivedate=2008-05-09 }}</ref>\n\nPlanetMath was started when the popular free online mathematics encyclopedia [[MathWorld]] was temporarily taken offline for 12 months by a court injunction as a result of the [[CRC Press]] lawsuit against the [[Wolfram Research]] company and its employee (and MathWorld's author) [[Eric Weisstein]].\n\n==Content==\n\nThe main PlanetMath focus is on  [[encyclopedia|encyclopedic]] entries.  It formerly operated a self-hosted forum, but now encourages discussion via [[Gitter]].\n\n{{As of|2013|02|15}}, the encyclopedia hosted about 9,289 entries and over 16,258 ''concepts'' (a concept may be for example a specific notion defined within a more general entry).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://planetmath.org/encyclopedia/|title=PlanetMath Encyclopedia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130215215112/http://planetmath.org/encyclopedia/|archivedate=2013-02-15}}</ref> An overview of the current PlanetMath contents is also available.\n<ref> Tutor City\n\n</ref>\n\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Best Tutor Agency|url=https://tutorcity.sg|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n\n<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tutorcity.sg |title=Tutor City |publisher=Tutor City |date=2013-03-21 |accessdate=2013-09-06 |}</ref> About 300 Wikipedia entries incorporate text from PlanetMath articles; they are listed in [[:Category:Wikipedia articles incorporating text from PlanetMath]].\n\nAn all-inclusive PlanetMath ''Free Encyclopedia'' book of 2,300 pages is available for the encyclopedia contents up to 2006 as a free download PDF file.<ref>[http://planetphysics.org/?op=getobj&from=books&id=207 PlanetMath \"''Free Encyclopedia''\" book] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160620044430/http://planetphysics.org/?op=getobj&from=books&id=207 |date=June 20, 2016 }} based on 2004-2005 content of PlanetMath</ref>\n\n===Content development model===\n\nPlanetMath implements a specific content creation system called ''authority model''.<ref>[http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj&from=collab&id=34 Noosphere's] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304034756/http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj&from=collab&id=34 |date=March 4, 2016 }} authority model</ref>.\n\nAn author who starts a new article becomes its ''owner'', that is the only person authorized to edit that article.  Other users may add corrections and discuss improvements but the resulting modifications of the article, if any, are always made by the owner.  However, if there are long lasting unresolved corrections, the ownership can be removed. More precisely, after 2 weeks the system starts to remind the owner by mail; at 6 weeks any user can \"adopt\" the article; at 8 weeks the ownership of the entry is completely removed (and such an entry is called \"orphaned\").\n\nTo make the development more smooth, the owner may also choose to grant editing rights to other individuals or groups.\n\nThe user can explicitly create links to other articles, and the system also automatically turns certain words into  links to the defining articles. The topic area of every article is classified by the [[Mathematics Subject Classification]] (MSC) of the [[American Mathematical Society]] (AMS).\n\nThe site is supervised by the Content Committee. Its basic mission is to  ''maintain the integrity and quality of the mathematical content and organization of PlanetMath.''<ref>{{cite web |author=Username * |url=http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj&from=collab&id=130 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101126222624/http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj&from=collab&id=130 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-11-26 |title=ContentCommittee Charter |publisher=Planetmath.org |accessdate=2013-09-06 }}</ref> As defined in its Charter, the tasks of the Committee include:\n* Developing/maintaining the standards for PlanetMath content\n* Improving individual PlanetMath entries in its Encyclopedia, Book, Paper, and Exposition)\n* Developing topic areas\n* Developing/improving site and user documentation\n* Managing the PlanetMath Request list and Unproved Theorems list\n* Improving categorization and other meta-attributes of entries.\n* Developing software recommendations for improved content authoring and editorial functions.\n\n===Technical details===\nPlanetMath content is licensed under the [[copyleft]] [[Creative Commons Attribution/Share-Alike License]].\nAll content is written in [[LaTeX]], a typesetting system popular among [[mathematician]]s because of its support of the technical needs of mathematical typesetting and its high-quality output.\n\nThe software running PlanetMath is written in [[Perl]] and runs on [[Linux]] and the web server [[apache server|Apache]]. It is known as ''No\u00f6sphere'' and has been released under the free [[BSD License]]. As of March 13, 2013 PlanetMath has retired No\u00f6sphere and runs now on a software called ''Planetary'', which itself was implemented with [[Drupal]].\n\n===Related projects===\nEncyclopedic content and bibliographic materials related to physics, mathematics and mathematical physics are developed by [[PlanetPhysics]]. The site, launched in 2005, uses similar software (Noosphere), but a significantly different moderation model with emphasis on current research in physics and peer review.<ref>[http://planetphysics.org/ PlanetPhysics.org] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225121156/http://planetphysics.org/ |date=February 25, 2009 }}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160620042751/http://planetphysics.org/?op=listobj&from=books Free Book downloads] in PDF format, Original Papers (~10 pages) and Expositions (>30 pages) {{dead link|date=May 2015}}</ref> Additionally, a PlanetComputing project is envisaged that would also include [[Computational Physics]] and [[Artificial intelligence|AI]] together with logical, categorical, ontological and mathematical foundations of computers and automata.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[arXiv]]\n* [[CogPrints]]\n* [[List of online encyclopedias]]\n* [[MathWorld]]\n* [[MathOverflow]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://planetphysics.org |title= PlanetPhysics |url-status= dead |archive-date= Feb 25, 2009 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090225121156/http://planetphysics.org/ }}\n* {{cite web |first= Aaron E. |last= Klemm |url= http://freesoftwaremagazine.com/articles/wiki_value/ |title= Motivation and value of free resources: Wikipedia and Planetmath show the way |date= Feb 16, 2005 |publisher= Free Software magazine }}\n* {{cite journal |url= http://www.dvara.net/HK/issue.pdf |journal= Free Software Magazine |issue= 1 |date= Feb 2005 |title= Motivation and value of free resources |pages= 52&ndash;56 |display-authors= 0 |first= Aaron E. |last= Klemm  }} \n* {{cite journal |series= Netwatch |title= Web Projects: Grassroots Math Guide |volume= 308 |issue= 5729 |date= 17 June 2005 |page= 1721 |doi= 10.1126/science.308.5729.1721e |journal= Science |publisher= [[American Association for the Advancement of Science|AAAS]] }}\n* {{cite book |first= Christoph |last= Lange |title= The Semantic Web: Research and Applications |series= European Semantic Web Conference (ESWC) |date= 2008 |pages= 832&ndash;837 |chapter= SWiM \u2013 A Semantic Wiki for Mathematical Knowledge Management |volume= 5021 | arxiv= 1003.5196 |doi= 10.1007/978-3-540-68234-9_68 |isbn= 978-3-540-68233-2 }}\n* {{cite arXiv |first1=Robert |last1=Milson |first2=Aaron |last2=Krowne |eprint=cs/0507028 |title=Adapting CBPP platforms for instructional use|year=2005 }}\n* {{cite journal |first=Alex M. |last=Andrew |title=Archives, mathematics encyclopaedia, dancing robots, ASC |journal=Kybernetes |date=2008 |volume=37 |issue=9/10 |pages=1466\u20131468 |doi=10.1108/03684920810907805}}\n\n[[Category:Mathematics websites]]\n[[Category:Online encyclopedias]]\n[[Category:Wiki communities]]\n[[Category:Canadian online encyclopedias]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox website\n| name             = PlanetMath\n| logo             = pmlogo.png\n| logo_size        = 182px\n| screenshot       =\n| caption          =\n| url              = {{URL|http://planetmath.org/}}\n| commercial       = No\n| owner            = PlanetMath.org, Ltd.\n| content_license  = [[CC-BY-SA]]\n| type             = [[Internet encyclopedia project]]\n| language         = [[English language|English]]\n| registration     = [[GitHub]] account required to edit sources via pull request\n| author           = Nathan Egge, Aaron Krowne\n| launch_date      =\n| current_status   = Inactive\n| revenue          =\n| alexa            = 320,431 ({{as of|2019|9|24|alt=September 2019}})<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web|url= https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/planetmath.org|title= Planetmath.org Site Info|publisher= [[Alexa Internet]]|accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n'''PlanetMath''' is a [[free content|free]], collaborative, online [[mathematics]] [[encyclopedia]].  The emphasis is on rigour, openness, [[pedagogy]], real-time content, interlinked content, and also  [[community]] of about 24,000 people with various maths interests. Intended to be comprehensive, the project is currently hosted by the [[University of Waterloo]]. The site is owned by a US-based nonprofit corporation, \"PlanetMath.org, Ltd\".<ref>Self-descriptions of PM {{cite web |url=http://planetmath.org/?op%3Dgetobj%26from%3Dcollab%26id%3D35#SECTION00021000000000000000 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-05-15 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826090901/http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj&from=collab&id=35 |archivedate=2016-08-26 }}, {{cite web |url=http://planetmath.org/?op%3Dabout |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-05-02 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611023918/http://planetmath.org/?op=about |archivedate=2016-06-11 }} {{cite web |url=http://aux.planetmath.org/doc/donate.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-05-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509123133/http://aux.planetmath.org/doc/donate.html |archivedate=2008-05-09 }}</ref>\n\nPlanetMath was started when the popular free online mathematics encyclopedia [[MathWorld]] was temporarily taken offline for 12 months by a court injunction as a result of the [[CRC Press]] lawsuit against the [[Wolfram Research]] company and its employee (and MathWorld's author) [[Eric Weisstein]].\n\n==Content==\n\nThe main PlanetMath focus is on  [[encyclopedia|encyclopedic]] entries.  It formerly operated a self-hosted forum, but now encourages discussion via [[Gitter]].\n\n{{As of|2013|02|15}}, the encyclopedia hosted about 9,289 entries and over 16,258 ''concepts'' (a concept may be for example a specific notion defined within a more general entry).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://planetmath.org/encyclopedia/|title=PlanetMath Encyclopedia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130215215112/http://planetmath.org/encyclopedia/|archivedate=2013-02-15}}</ref> An overview of the current PlanetMath contents is also available.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://planetmath.org/encyclopedia/OverviewOfTheContentOfPlanetMath.html |title=Overview of the content of PlanetMath |publisher=Planetmath.org |date=2013-03-21 |accessdate=2013-09-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120804090402/http://planetmath.org/encyclopedia/OverviewOfTheContentOfPlanetMath.html |archivedate=2012-08-04 }}</ref> About 300 Wikipedia entries incorporate text from PlanetMath articles; they are listed in [[:Category:Wikipedia articles incorporating text from PlanetMath]].\n\nAn all-inclusive PlanetMath ''Free Encyclopedia'' book of 2,300 pages is available for the encyclopedia contents up to 2006 as a free download PDF file.<ref>[http://planetphysics.org/?op=getobj&from=books&id=207 PlanetMath \"''Free Encyclopedia''\" book] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160620044430/http://planetphysics.org/?op=getobj&from=books&id=207 |date=June 20, 2016 }} based on 2004-2005 content of PlanetMath</ref>\n\n===Content development model===\n\nPlanetMath implements a specific content creation system called ''authority model''.<ref>[http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj&from=collab&id=34 Noosphere's] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304034756/http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj&from=collab&id=34 |date=March 4, 2016 }} authority model</ref>.\n\nAn author who starts a new article becomes its ''owner'', that is the only person authorized to edit that article.  Other users may add corrections and discuss improvements but the resulting modifications of the article, if any, are always made by the owner.  However, if there are long lasting unresolved corrections, the ownership can be removed. More precisely, after 2 weeks the system starts to remind the owner by mail; at 6 weeks any user can \"adopt\" the article; at 8 weeks the ownership of the entry is completely removed (and such an entry is called \"orphaned\").\n\nTo make the development more smooth, the owner may also choose to grant editing rights to other individuals or groups.\n\nThe user can explicitly create links to other articles, and the system also automatically turns certain words into  links to the defining articles. The topic area of every article is classified by the [[Mathematics Subject Classification]] (MSC) of the [[American Mathematical Society]] (AMS).\n\nThe site is supervised by the Content Committee. Its basic mission is to  ''maintain the integrity and quality of the mathematical content and organization of PlanetMath.''<ref>{{cite web |author=Username * |url=http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj&from=collab&id=130 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101126222624/http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj&from=collab&id=130 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-11-26 |title=ContentCommittee Charter |publisher=Planetmath.org |accessdate=2013-09-06 }}</ref> As defined in its Charter, the tasks of the Committee include:\n* Developing/maintaining the standards for PlanetMath content\n* Improving individual PlanetMath entries in its Encyclopedia, Book, Paper, and Exposition)\n* Developing topic areas\n* Developing/improving site and user documentation\n* Managing the PlanetMath Request list and Unproved Theorems list\n* Improving categorization and other meta-attributes of entries.\n* Developing software recommendations for improved content authoring and editorial functions.\n\n===Technical details===\nPlanetMath content is licensed under the [[copyleft]] [[Creative Commons Attribution/Share-Alike License]].\nAll content is written in [[LaTeX]], a typesetting system popular among [[mathematician]]s because of its support of the technical needs of mathematical typesetting and its high-quality output.\n\nThe software running PlanetMath is written in [[Perl]] and runs on [[Linux]] and the web server [[apache server|Apache]]. It is known as ''No\u00f6sphere'' and has been released under the free [[BSD License]]. As of March 13, 2013 PlanetMath has retired No\u00f6sphere and runs now on a software called ''Planetary'', which itself was implemented with [[Drupal]].\n\n===Related projects===\nEncyclopedic content and bibliographic materials related to physics, mathematics and mathematical physics are developed by [[PlanetPhysics]]. The site, launched in 2005, uses similar software (Noosphere), but a significantly different moderation model with emphasis on current research in physics and peer review.<ref>[http://planetphysics.org/ PlanetPhysics.org] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225121156/http://planetphysics.org/ |date=February 25, 2009 }}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160620042751/http://planetphysics.org/?op=listobj&from=books Free Book downloads] in PDF format, Original Papers (~10 pages) and Expositions (>30 pages) {{dead link|date=May 2015}}</ref> Additionally, a PlanetComputing project is envisaged that would also include [[Computational Physics]] and [[Artificial intelligence|AI]] together with logical, categorical, ontological and mathematical foundations of computers and automata.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[arXiv]]\n* [[CogPrints]]\n* [[List of online encyclopedias]]\n* [[MathWorld]]\n* [[MathOverflow]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://planetphysics.org |title= PlanetPhysics |url-status= dead |archive-date= Feb 25, 2009 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090225121156/http://planetphysics.org/ }}\n* {{cite web |first= Aaron E. |last= Klemm |url= http://freesoftwaremagazine.com/articles/wiki_value/ |title= Motivation and value of free resources: Wikipedia and Planetmath show the way |date= Feb 16, 2005 |publisher= Free Software magazine }}\n* {{cite journal |url= http://www.dvara.net/HK/issue.pdf |journal= Free Software Magazine |issue= 1 |date= Feb 2005 |title= Motivation and value of free resources |pages= 52&ndash;56 |display-authors= 0 |first= Aaron E. |last= Klemm  }} \n* {{cite journal |series= Netwatch |title= Web Projects: Grassroots Math Guide |volume= 308 |issue= 5729 |date= 17 June 2005 |page= 1721 |doi= 10.1126/science.308.5729.1721e |journal= Science |publisher= [[American Association for the Advancement of Science|AAAS]] }}\n* {{cite book |first= Christoph |last= Lange |title= The Semantic Web: Research and Applications |series= European Semantic Web Conference (ESWC) |date= 2008 |pages= 832&ndash;837 |chapter= SWiM \u2013 A Semantic Wiki for Mathematical Knowledge Management |volume= 5021 | arxiv= 1003.5196 |doi= 10.1007/978-3-540-68234-9_68 |isbn= 978-3-540-68233-2 }}\n* {{cite arXiv |first1=Robert |last1=Milson |first2=Aaron |last2=Krowne |eprint=cs/0507028 |title=Adapting CBPP platforms for instructional use|year=2005 }}\n* {{cite journal |first=Alex M. |last=Andrew |title=Archives, mathematics encyclopaedia, dancing robots, ASC |journal=Kybernetes |date=2008 |volume=37 |issue=9/10 |pages=1466\u20131468 |doi=10.1108/03684920810907805}}\n\n[[Category:Mathematics websites]]\n[[Category:Online encyclopedias]]\n[[Category:Wiki communities]]\n[[Category:Canadian online encyclopedias]]\n", "name_user": "AOi901", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PlanetMath"}
{"title_page": "Border ware", "text_new": "[[File:16th_century_Border_Ware_tall_jug.jpg|thumb|16th century Border ware jug]]\n\n'''Border ware''' is a type of post-medieval [[Great Britain|British]] pottery commonly used in [[London]] during the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries. The lead-glazed, sandy earthenware was produced from kilns along the border between [[Hampshire]] and [[Surrey]]. There are two classes of Border ware, fine whitewares and fine redwares. \n\n==History==\nBorder ware evolved from a medieval pottery known as [[Surrey whiteware]]. Surrey whiteware consisted of four classes: [[Kingston upon Thames|Kingston-type]] ware, Coarse Border ware, [[Cheam]] whiteware  and Tudor Green ware. The earlier whitewares were produced from the 13th to the 16th centuries.{{sfn|Vince|1985|p=76}}{{sfn|Pearce|1988|p=7}}\n\nBorder ware was manufactured in the Surrey-Hampshire border area from the 16th century to the 19th centuries, although the whitewares were produced only during the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries. The  demand for whitewares declined during the 17th century while the demand for redwares increased..{{sfn|Holling|1971|p=64}} The production of whitewares ended most likely during the early 18th century; Redwares continued to be produced until the 19th century.{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=1}}\n\n==Description==\n[[File:16th_century_Border_ware_flask.jpg|thumb|Border ware flask, 16th century]]\nThe term, \"Border ware\" was introduced by [[Archaeologist|archaeologist]], Clive Orton, to describe the lead-glazed, sandy earthenware produced along the Surrey-Hampshire borders during the early post-medieval period. The pottery is divided into two classes, whitewares and redwares, although the term \"Border ware\" generally refers to the whitewares. The redwares are known as \"Red Border ware.{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=1}}\n\n===Fabrics===\nWhiteware fabrics are generally hard with a smooth and fine texture. Fabric colours include off-white, yellow, brown, buff, olive and pinkish grey. Glazes are often [[Crazing|crazed]] and finishes range from thin and spotty to thick and glossy. Glaze colours include yellow, brown, olive clear, and green.{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=5}}\n\nRedware fabrics range from smooth to slightly rough in feel. Fabric colours generally range from brick red to reddish-yellow. Finishes range from thin and uneven to thick and glossy. A clear lead glaze was often used, giving the pottery products an orange or reddish-brown colour. Other glaze colours include olive, brown and green. Green glaze was created by potters by adding copper to lead glaze.{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=6}}\n\n===Forms===\nPottery products were traditional household items commonly used during the post-medieval period.{{sfn|Holling|1971|p=69}} [[Skillet|Skillets]], saucepans, chafing dishes and [[Pipkin|tripod pipkins]] were common cookware products manufactured by the Border ware pottery industry.\n[[File:Border_ware_porridger_yellow-glaze.jpg|thumb|left||Border ware porringer]]\nBorder ware forms used for serving and storing food begin with dishes, which are divided into flanged dishes and deep dishes. Bowls were manufactured in a wide variety of shapes and sizes: wide bowls, deep bowls, bowls with handles, and [[Porringer|porringers]]. Vessels for storing and serving liquids include drinking [[Jug|jugs]], [[Cup|cups]], goblets and [[Mug|mugs]]. \n\nOther Border ware forms include costrels (portable flasks), which can be divided into two categories, mammiform costrels and bottle shaped costrels. [[Candlestick|Candlesticks]] were two styles: upright and saucer. There were also [[Lantern|lanterns]], [[Chamber pot|chamber pots]], [[Tudor money box|money boxes]], [[Jar|jars]], double dishes, [[Whistle|whistles]], fuming pots and [[Colander|strainers]].\n\n==Production==\n{{Quote box\n|width     =15em\n|border    = 2px\n|align     = right\n|bgcolor   = #FFFACD\t\t\n|fontsize  = 85%\n|title_bg  =\n|title_fnt =\n|title     =\n|quote     = \"The Hampshire-Surrey border potters had a natural advantage through an accident of geology which is not repeated in other areas near London north of the Thames, nor in Kent, and it applied to every kind of vessel they produced.\"\n|salign    = right\n|source=\u2014 ''F.W. Holling'', 1971.{{sfn|Holling|1971|p=65}}}}\n\n===Clay Sources===\n\nThe source of the white-firing clays used to produce Surrey whitewares was the [[Reading Formation|Reading Beds]] along the borders of Hampshire and [[Berkshire]]. The Reading beds between [[Farnham]] and [[Tongham]] were the best source of potting clay for medieval potters producing wares for the London market. These outcrops of white-firing and red-firing clay deposits had provided an abundant source of clays for pottery manufacturing since the early [[Roman Britain|Roman period]].{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=3}}\n\n===Pottery sites===\nBorder ware manufacturing sites were selected for their proximity to plentiful clay and fuel supplies.{{sfn|Holling|1971|p=63}}\nThe area northeast of [[Farnham]] became the center of the Border ware pottery industry. Three sites have been identified as producing the pottery best representing Border Ware fabrics, forms and glazes. These sites are: ''Farnborough Hill Convent'' in [[Farnborough]], Hampshire, Ye Old Malthouse in [[Hawley]], Hampshire and ''The Lime'', [[Ash]], Surrey.{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=2}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Stamford ware]]\n*[[Surrey whiteware]]\n*[[Humber ware]]\n*[[Bartmann jug]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=150px heights=150px perrow=6\">\nBorder ware jar green-glaze.jpg||Green-glazed Border ware jar \nBorder ware candlestick.jpg|Border ware candlestick \nBorder_ware_small_bowl.jpg|Border ware bowl\nBorder_ware_jug.jpg| Border ware jug\nBorder_ware_pipkin_green-glazed.jpg|Border ware pipkin\nKingston-type_jug_round.jpg||Surrey whiteware \n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite journal |last1=Holling |first1=F.W. |title=A preliminary note on the pottery industry of the Hampshire-Surrey Borders |journal=Surrey Archaeological Collections |date=1971 |volume=68 |pages=57-88|url=https://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archives/view/surreyac/contents.cfm?vol=68 |accessdate=4 April 2020|ref=harv}} \n\n*{{cite book|last1=Pearce|first1=Jaqueline ||last2=Vince|first2=Alan |title=Surrey Whitewares\n|year=1988|isbn= 978-0903290340|location=London |publisher=London & Middlesex Archaeological societies |ref=harv}}\n\n*{{cite book|last1=Pearce|first1=Jaqueline |title=Border Wares. Post-Medieval Pottery in London 1500-1700|year=1992|isbn=978-0112904946|location=London |publisher=Museum of London |ref=harv}}\n\n*{{cite journal |last1=Vince |first1=A.G. |title=The Saxon and Medieval Pottery of London: A Review |journal=Journal of Medieval Archaeology |date=1985 |volume=29 |pages=29-83 |url=https://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archiveDS/archiveDownload?t=arch-769-1/dissemination/pdf/vol29/29_025_093.pdf |accessdate=4 April 2020|ref=harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last1=Laing |first1=Lloyd |title=Pottery in Britain 4000 BC to AD 1900 |date=2003 |publisher=Greenlight Publishing |isbn=978-1897738146}} \n*{{cite book |last1=McCarthy |first1=Michael |last2=Brooks |first2=Catherine M. |title=Medieval Pottery in Britain, Ad 900-1600 |date=1995 |publisher=Leicester University Press |isbn=978-0718512712}} \n\n==External links==\n*[http://friendsofwhitehallcheam.co.uk/index.php/past-events/ The Time Cheam Project]\n\n{{Pottery}}\n \n[[Category:British pottery]]\n[[Category:16th century in England]]\n[[Category:17th century in England]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:16th_century_Border_Ware_tall_jug.jpg|thumb|16th century Border ware jug]]\n\n'''Border ware''' is a type of post-medieval [[Great Britain|British]] pottery commonly used in [[London]] during the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries. The lead-glazed, sandy earthenware was produced from kilns along the border between [[Hampshire]] and [[Surrey]]. There are two classes of Border ware, fine whitewares and fine redwares. \n\n==History==\nBorder ware evolved from a medieval pottery known as [[Surrey whiteware]]. Surrey whitewares, also produced from kilns along the Surrey-Hampshire borders, consisted of four classes: [[Kingston upon Thames|Kingston-type]] ware, Coarse Border ware, [[Cheam]] whiteware  and Tudor Green ware. Surrey whitewares were produced from the 13th to the 16th centuries.{{sfn|Vince|1985|p=76}}{{sfn|Pearce|1988|p=7}}\n\nPottery was manufactured in the Surrey-Hampshire border area from the 16th century to the 19th centuries, although whitewares were produced only during the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries. The  demand for whitewares declined during the 17th century while the demand for redwares increased..{{sfn|Holling|1971|p=64}} The production of whitewares ended most likely during the early 18th century; Redwares continued to be produced until the 19th century.{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=1}}\n\n==Description==\n[[File:16th_century_Border_ware_flask.jpg|thumb|Border ware flask, 16th century]]\nThe term, \"Border ware\" was introduced by [[Archaeologist|archaeologist]], Clive Orton, to describe the lead-glazed, sandy earthenware produced along the Surrey-Hampshire borders during the early post-medieval period. The pottery is divided into two classes, whitewares and redwares, although the term \"Border ware\" generally refers to the whitewares. The redwares are known as \"Red Border ware.{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=1}}\n\n===Fabrics===\nWhiteware fabrics are generally hard with a smooth and fine texture. Fabric colours include off-white, yellow, brown, buff, olive and pinkish grey. Glazes are often [[Crazing|crazed]] and finishes range from thin and spotty to thick and glossy. Glaze colours include yellow, brown, olive clear, and green.{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=5}}\n\nRedware fabrics range from smooth to slightly rough in feel. Fabric colours generally range from brick red to reddish-yellow. Finishes range from thin and uneven to thick and glossy. A clear lead glaze was often used, giving the pottery products an orange or reddish-brown colour. Other glaze colours include olive, brown and green. Green glaze was created by potters by adding copper to lead glaze.{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=6}}\n\n===Forms===\nPottery products were traditional household items commonly used during the post-medieval period.{{sfn|Holling|1971|p=69}} [[Skillet|Skillets]], saucepans, chafing dishes and [[Pipkin|tripod pipkins]] were common cookware products manufactured by the Border ware pottery industry.\n[[File:Border_ware_porridger_yellow-glaze.jpg|thumb|left||Border ware porringer]]\nBorder ware forms used for serving and storing food begin with dishes, which are divided into flanged dishes and deep dishes. Bowls were manufactured in a wide variety of shapes and sizes: wide bowls, deep bowls, bowls with handles, and [[Porringer|porringers]]. Vessels for storing and serving liquids include drinking [[Jug|jugs]], [[Cup|cups]], goblets and [[Mug|mugs]]. \n\nOther Border ware forms include costrels (portable flasks), which can be divided into two categories, mammiform costrels and bottle shaped costrels. [[Candlestick|Candlesticks]] were two styles: upright and saucer. There were also [[Lantern|lanterns]], [[Chamber pot|chamber pots]], [[Tudor money box|money boxes]], [[Jar|jars]], double dishes, [[Whistle|whistles]], fuming pots and [[Colander|strainers]].\n\n==Production==\n{{Quote box\n|width     =15em\n|border    = 2px\n|align     = right\n|bgcolor   = #FFFACD\t\t\n|fontsize  = 85%\n|title_bg  =\n|title_fnt =\n|title     =\n|quote     = \"The Hampshire-Surrey border potters had a natural advantage through an accident of geology which is not repeated in other areas near London north of the Thames, nor in Kent, and it applied to every kind of vessel they produced.\"\n|salign    = right\n|source=\u2014 ''F.W. Holling'', 1971.{{sfn|Holling|1971|p=65}}}}\n\n===Clay Sources===\n\nThe source of the white-firing clays used to produce Surrey whitewares was the [[Reading Formation|Reading Beds]] along the borders of Hampshire and [[Berkshire]]. The Reading beds between [[Farnham]] and [[Tongham]] were the best source of potting clay for medieval potters producing wares for the London market. These outcrops of white-firing and red-firing clay deposits had provided an abundant source of clays for pottery manufacturing since the early [[Roman Britain|Roman period]].{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=3}}\n\n===Pottery sites===\nBorder ware manufacturing sites were selected for their proximity to plentiful clay and fuel supplies.{{sfn|Holling|1971|p=63}}\nThe area northeast of [[Farnham]] became the center of the Border ware pottery industry. Three sites have been identified as producing the pottery best representing Border Ware fabrics, forms and glazes. These sites are: ''Farnborough Hill Convent'' in [[Farnborough]], Hampshire, Ye Old Malthouse in [[Hawley]], Hampshire and ''The Lime'', [[Ash]], Surrey.{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=2}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Stamford ware]]\n*[[Surrey whiteware]]\n*[[Humber ware]]\n*[[Bartmann jug]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=150px heights=150px perrow=6\">\nBorder ware jar green-glaze.jpg||Green-glazed Border ware jar \nBorder ware candlestick.jpg|Border ware candlestick \nBorder_ware_small_bowl.jpg|Border ware bowl\nBorder_ware_jug.jpg| Border ware jug\nBorder_ware_pipkin_green-glazed.jpg|Border ware pipkin\nKingston-type_jug_round.jpg||Surrey whiteware \n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite journal |last1=Holling |first1=F.W. |title=A preliminary note on the pottery industry of the Hampshire-Surrey Borders |journal=Surrey Archaeological Collections |date=1971 |volume=68 |pages=57-88|url=https://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archives/view/surreyac/contents.cfm?vol=68 |accessdate=4 April 2020|ref=harv}} \n\n*{{cite book|last1=Pearce|first1=Jaqueline ||last2=Vince|first2=Alan |title=Surrey Whitewares\n|year=1988|isbn= 978-0903290340|location=London |publisher=London & Middlesex Archaeological societies |ref=harv}}\n\n*{{cite book|last1=Pearce|first1=Jaqueline |title=Border Wares. Post-Medieval Pottery in London 1500-1700|year=1992|isbn=978-0112904946|location=London |publisher=Museum of London |ref=harv}}\n\n*{{cite journal |last1=Vince |first1=A.G. |title=The Saxon and Medieval Pottery of London: A Review |journal=Journal of Medieval Archaeology |date=1985 |volume=29 |pages=29-83 |url=https://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archiveDS/archiveDownload?t=arch-769-1/dissemination/pdf/vol29/29_025_093.pdf |accessdate=4 April 2020|ref=harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last1=Laing |first1=Lloyd |title=Pottery in Britain 4000 BC to AD 1900 |date=2003 |publisher=Greenlight Publishing |isbn=978-1897738146}} \n*{{cite book |last1=McCarthy |first1=Michael |last2=Brooks |first2=Catherine M. |title=Medieval Pottery in Britain, Ad 900-1600 |date=1995 |publisher=Leicester University Press |isbn=978-0718512712}} \n\n==External links==\n*[http://friendsofwhitehallcheam.co.uk/index.php/past-events/ The Time Cheam Project]\n\n{{Pottery}}\n \n[[Category:British pottery]]\n[[Category:16th century in England]]\n[[Category:17th century in England]]\n", "name_user": "MauraWen", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:fixed sentences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Border_ware"}
{"title_page": "Siege of Patras (1821)", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=March 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Siege of Patras\n|partof=the [[Greek War of Independence]]\n|image= I Katalipsi ton Patron - by Hess.jpg\n|image_size= 200px\n|caption=''[[Athanasios Kanakaris]] during the siege of Patras'' by [[Peter von Hess]]\n|date=March 1821\n|place=[[Patras]], [[Greece]]\n|casus=\n|territory=\n|result=Capture of the city by the Greeks, creation of the [[Directorate of Achaea]], failure to capture the fortress\n|combatant1=[[Image:Flag of Greece (1821).svg|border|22px]] [[Greek War of Independence|Greek revolutionaries]]\n|combatant2={{flagcountry|Ottoman Empire|1453}}\n|commander1=[[Image:Flag of Greece (1821).svg|20px]] [[Germanos III of Old Patras|Germanos of Patras]]<br> [[Image:Flag of Greece (1821).svg|20px]] [[Athanasios Kanakaris]]<br> [[File:Andreas Londos Flag 1821.svg|20px]] [[Andreas Londos]]<br> [[Image:Flag of Greece (1821).svg|20px]] [[Benizelos Rouphos]]<br> [[Image:Flag of Greece (1821).svg|20px]] [[Panagiotis Karatzas]]<br> [[Image:Flag of Greece (1821).svg|20px]] [[Ioannis Papadiamantopoulos (elder)|Ioannis Papadiamantopoulos]]\n|commander2= Unknown\n|strength1=1,500 irregulars\n|strength2=\n|casualties1=unknown\n|casualties2=unknown\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Greek War of Independence}}\n[[File:\u0394\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03ae\u03c1\u03c5\u03be\u03b7 \u03b5\u03c0\u03b1\u03bd\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c4\u03ce\u03bd \u03a0\u03ac\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 1821.jpg|thumb|180px|Declaration by the revolutionaries of Patras, engraved on a stele in the city]]\n\nThe '''Siege of Patras''' was one of the first events of the [[Greek War of Independence]] (1821-1830). After the outbreak of the revolution, the Greeks under the leadership of the primates of Patras, captured the city and destroyed the Muslem quarter. The Greeks tried to capture also the main [[Patras Castle|fortress]] of the city. \n\nIn April, an Ottoman army lifted the siege and destroyed a large part of the city, with [[Patras]] remaining under Ottoman control almost until the end of the war (1828).\n\nConsul of France in the city at the time was Hugo Pouqueville, brother of [[Fran\u00e7ois Pouqueville]], and for Great Britain Philip James Green.\n\n==Aftermath==\n\nIn February 1822, after a victorious battle outside Patras (Battle of Girokomio), the Greeks under [[Theodoros Kolokotronis]] began again the siege of the fortress. It was after the defeat in the [[Battle of Peta]], which allowed the Ottoman army to pass to [[Achaea]], and the [[Expedition of Dramali]] that brought an end to the siege.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Greek War of Independence|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{coord|38.2500|N|21.7333|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1821]]\n[[Category:Sieges of the Greek War of Independence|Patras]]\n[[Category:History of Patras]]\n[[Category:1821 in Greece]]\n[[Category:1821 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:March 1821 events]]\n[[Category:Peloponnese in the Greek War of Independence]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=March 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Siege of Patras\n|partof=the [[Greek War of Independence]]\n|image= I Katalipsi ton Patron - by Hess.jpg\n|image_size= 200px\n|caption=''[[Athanasios Kanakaris]] during the siege of Patras'' by [[Peter von Hess]]\n|date=March 1821\n|place=[[Patras]], [[Greece]]\n|casus=\n|territory=\n|result=Capture of the city by the Greeks, creation of the [[Directorate of Achaea]], failure to capture the fortress\n|combatant1=[[Image:Flag of Greece (1821).svg|border|22px]] [[Greek War of Independence|Greek revolutionaries]]\n|combatant2={{flagcountry|Ottoman Empire|1453}}\n|commander1=[[Image:Flag of Greece (1821).svg|20px]] [[Germanos III of Old Patras|Germanos of Patras]]<br> [[Image:Flag of Greece (1821).svg|20px]][[Athanasios Kanakaris]]<br> [[File:Andreas Londos Flag 1821.svg|20px]] [[Andreas Londos]]<br> [[Image:Flag of Greece (1821).svg|20px]] [[Benizelos Rouphos]]<br> [[Image:Flag of Greece (1821).svg|20px]] [[Panagiotis Karatzas]]<br> [[Image:Flag of Greece (1821).svg|20px]] [[Ioannis Papadiamantopoulos (elder)|Ioannis Papadiamantopoulos]]\n|commander2= Unknown\n|strength1=1,500 irregulars\n|strength2=\n|casualties1=unknown\n|casualties2=unknown\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Greek War of Independence}}\n[[File:\u0394\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03ae\u03c1\u03c5\u03be\u03b7 \u03b5\u03c0\u03b1\u03bd\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c4\u03ce\u03bd \u03a0\u03ac\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 1821.jpg|thumb|180px|Declaration by the revolutionaries of Patras, engraved on a stele in the city]]\n\nThe '''Siege of Patras''' was one of the first events of the [[Greek War of Independence]] (1821-1830). After the outbreak of the revolution, Greek under the leadership of the primates of Patras, captured the city and destroyed the Muslem quarter. The Greeks tried to capture also the main [[Patras Castle|fortress]] of the city. \n\nIn April, an Ottoman army lifted the siege and destroyed a large part of the city, with [[Patras]] remaining under Ottoman control almost until the end of the war (1828).\n\nConsul of France of the city at the time was Hugo Pouqueville, brother of [[Fran\u00e7ois Pouqueville]], and for Great Britain Philip James Green.\n\n==Aftermath==\n\nIn February 1822, after a victorious battle outside Patras (Battle of Girokomio), the Greeks under [[Theodoros Kolokotronis]] began again the siege of the fortress. It was after the defeat in the [[Battle of Peta]], which allowed the Ottoman army to pass to [[Achaea]], and the [[Expedition of Dramali]] that brought an end to the siege.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Greek War of Independence|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{coord|38.2500|N|21.7333|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1821]]\n[[Category:Sieges of the Greek War of Independence|Patras]]\n[[Category:History of Patras]]\n[[Category:1821 in Greece]]\n[[Category:1821 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:March 1821 events]]\n[[Category:Peloponnese in the Greek War of Independence]]\n", "name_user": "Greco22", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siege_of_Patras_(1821)"}
{"title_page": "Attila the Stockbroker", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{autobiography|date=September 2018}}\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2018}}\n}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = Attila the Stockbroker\n|image           = Attila The Stockbroker, Calstock 21.jpg\n|caption         = Attila the Stockbroker (centre, playing violin) performing with Barnstormer 1649 at Calstock Hall. September 2018.\n|background      = solo_singer\n|birth_name      = John Baine\n|birth_date      = {{birth date and age|df=y|1957|10|21}}\n|birth_place     = [[Southwick, West Sussex|Southwick]], [[Sussex]], England\n|death_date      = \n|instrument      = [[Singing|Vocals]], [[Mandola]], Violin, Viola, Mandocello,  Recorders, Crumhorn,Rackett,  Cornamuse, Shawm, Rauschpfeife, Bombarde\n|genre           = [[Punk rock]], [[punk poetry]], [[folk punk]], [[Early music]]\n|occupation      = [[Singing|Singer]], [[songwriter]], [[poetry|poet]]\n|years_active    = Late 70s&ndash;present\n|label           = [[Cherry Red Records|Cherry Red]], [[Probe Plus]], Roundhead Records\n|associated_acts = [[Barnstormer 1649]], [[English Disease (band)|English Disease]], [[Brighton Riot Squad]], [[Contingent]], [[John Otway]]\n|website         = [http://www.attilathestockbroker.com attilathestockbroker.com]\n}}\n'''John Baine''' (born 21 October 1957), better known by his stage name '''Attila the Stockbroker''',<ref name=\"Strong\">Strong, Martin C. (2003) ''The Great Indie Discography'', Canongate, {{ISBN|1-84195-335-0}}, p. 208</ref> is a [[Punk literature|punk poet]], multi instrumentalist musician and songwriter. He performs solo and as the leader of the band Barnstormer 1649, who combine early music and punk. He has performed over 3,300 concerts, published eight books of poems and an autobiography (which itself has 38 poems in it) and released over forty recordings (albums and singles).<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguide/comedy/story/0,,1872259,00.html | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=Comedy preview: 16 Sep}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.attilathestockbroker.com/discog.html |title=Discography |publisher=Attila the Stockbroker |date=9 January 2005 |accessdate=2013-06-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526015103/http://www.attilathestockbroker.com/discog.html |archivedate=26 May 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n{{BLP sources section|date=October 2015}}\nBaine attended the [[University of Kent]], Darwin College, in [[Canterbury]] between 1975 and 1978 graduating with a 2:2 degree in French and Politics.<ref name=oxfordref>[http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/oi/authority.20110803095433690 Attila the Stockbroker At Oxford Reference]. Retrieved 5 June 2016</ref> Baine took the performing name Attila the Stockbroker during a short stint as a City stockbroker's clerk between 1980 and 1981 because a colleague accused him of having the eating habits of [[Attila the Hun]].\n\n==Career==\nHaving started performing in the late 1970s after being inspired by the spirit and 'do it yourself' ethos of the [[punk subculture]], particularly [[The Clash]]'s overtly [[Socialism|socialist]] stance, Baine was briefly bass player in punk bands English Disease and Brighton Riot Squad, and spent some time in 1979 in Brussels playing bass in Belgian band Contingent before going solo. (Contingent have now reformed and still gig from time to time)<ref name=\"Strong\" /> He did his first gig as Attila the Stockbroker at Bush Fair Playbarn, [[Harlow, Essex]], on 8 September 1980. At first he performed poems and songs in between bands at [[punk rock]] concerts, accompanying himself on the phased [[electric mandolin]]. After this was smashed over his head by [[Fascism|fascists]] during a fight at a performance in [[North London]] in May 1982, he got a [[mandola]] (a [[Perfect fifth|fifth]] lower) and has played this ever since. He has performed in 24 countries, playing venues ranging from the [[Oxford Union]] in England to [[Squatting|squatted]] punk clubs in Germany, and performs between 80 and 100 shows every year, sometimes more. He toured [[East Germany]] four times before the [[Berlin Wall]] came down, performed in a hotel in [[Enver Hoxha]]'s [[Albania]] and had to turn down the opportunity to perform in North Korea (at the World Festival of Youth & Students in 1989) because he was already booked to tour Canada. He was signed by [[Cherry Red Records|Cherry Red]] in 1982 after recording a session for [[John Peel]]'s [[BBC Radio 1]] show.<ref name=\"Strong\" /> He recorded a second session for Peel in 1983.<ref name=\"KIP\">\"[http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/johnpeel/artists/a/attilathestockbr/ Attila The Stockbroker]\", ''Keeping It Peel'', [[BBC]], retrieved 2010-10-16</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s, he was often the support act for punk bands, including [[The Jam]], [[The Alarm]], [[Newtown Neurotics]], [[New Model Army (band)|New Model Army]] and performed extensively with fellow punk-inspired ranting poets Swift Nick (Nick Swift), Kool Knotes (Richard Edwards), Porky the Poet ([[Phill Jupitus]]) and Seething Wells ([[Steven Wells]]). [[Manic Street Preachers]] supported him at a performance at [[Swansea University]]. In the 1990s, alongside many other things, he toured with [[John Otway]] as Headbutts and Halibuts, and together they wrote a surreal rock opera called ''Cheryl'', a tale of [[Satanism]], [[Trainspotting (hobby)|trainspotting]], drug abuse and unrequited love. He has performed at every [[Glastonbury Festival]] since 1983,at the Edinburgh Fringe on and off for 35 years,  and continues to write topical, satirical material on all kinds of subjects. He puts on an annual beer and music festival 'Glastonwick', currently held at Coombes Farm, near Shoreham though originally in Southwick, his home town nearby. June 2018 saw the 23rd Glastonwick.\n\nNotable works from the 1980s include the poem \"Contributory Negligence\"; various Russian-themed poems, satirizing the alleged [[Cold War]] Russian threat in the context of [[Margaret Thatcher]]'s Britain (such as \"Russians in the [[Department of Health and Social Security|DHSS]]\" and \"Russians in [[McDonald's]]\"). Other political poems include the surreal ''Nigel'' series, such as \"Nigel wants to go to [[C&A]]\". Later pieces include \"Asylum Seeking [[Dalek]]s\", which satirises the [[Right-wing politics|right wing]] press's attitudes to immigration, and \"Hey Celebrity\", which rejects the need for the concept of celebrity.\n\nAttila the Stockbroker formed the band '''Barnstormer''' in 1994, with the initial aim of combining punk rock and early music, which they did to an extent on their debut album ''The Siege of Shoreham'' in 1996. Then Barnstormer's line up changed: they turned into a melodic punk band and for the next 22 years performed regularly across Europe, doing over 500 gigs and releasing three further albums, ''Just One Life'' (2000) ''Zero Tolerance'' (2004) and ''Bankers and Looters'' (2012). In 2018 Attila, who has always been interested in the history of the radical movements spawned in the aftermath of the English Civil War, wrote and recorded an album, ''Restoration Tragedy'' on that theme, combining early music and punk. He changed the name of the band to Barnstormer 1649 (the year of Charles 1st's execution and the  revolutionary uprisings by the [[Levellers]] and [[Diggers]]).\n\n'''Barnstormer 1649''' features Attila on vocals, mandola, violin, viola, crumhorn, cornemuse, shawm, bombarde, rauschpfeife  and recorders; Jason Pegg (formerly of Clearlake) on guitar/backing vocals; M. M. McGhee on drums; Dave Cook (also of Too Many Crooks) on bass/backing vocals and Tim O'Tay on recorders.\n\nAttila now is still doing many solo shows combining his poems and songs. He has released three CDs featuring live recordings of solo gigs: ''Live in Belfast'' (2003) ''Live in Norway'' (2007) and 'Live at the Greys' (2014) His latest book of poems, 'Undaunted' was published in 2017, 'UK Gin Dependence Party and Other Peculiarities' 'in January 2014; ''My Poetic Licence'' came out in 2008. In 2010 he published a pamphlet, ''The Long Goodbye'', containing two poems \u2014 a long one dedicated to and chronicling the life of his mother Muriel, who died in June 2010 after a six-year battle with [[Alzheimer's Disease]], and a shorter one written for his stepfather John Stanford, who died in December 2009. ''The Long Goodbye'' was featured on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Woman's Hour]]'' on Mother's Day 2011.  Attila celebrated 30 years of performing in September 2010 with a 27-date tour of the UK, Germany and the Netherlands. In March 2011 he toured Australia and New Zealand for the first time in ten years, in 2012 made a return to Albania and in February 2014 toured the UK, Germany and Switzerland to promote his latest poetry book. In 2018 he performed at the Limerick Limerick Festival and continues to tour mainland Europe.\n\nOn 8 September 2015, the 35th anniversary of his first gig, it saw the publication of his autobiography, ''Arguments Yard (35 Years of Ranting Verse and Thrash Mandola)'' by Cherry Red Books.\n\nIn September 2016, Baine performed at the Keep Corbyn rally in Brighton in support of [[2016 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|Jeremy Corbyn's campaign]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|Labour Party leadership election]].<ref name=\"doncasterfreepress\">{{cite news |last=Burke|first=Darren|url=https://www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk/news/tv-star-comedians-line-up-for-jeremy-corbyn-rally-in-doncaster-1-8090226|title=TV star comedians line up for Jeremy Corbyn rally in Doncaster|location=Doncaster|newspaper=[[Doncaster Free Press]]|date=26 August 2016|accessdate=1 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 a short documentary ''35 Years A Punk Poet'' about Attila's performance career was produced by film maker Farouq Suleiman.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://repeatfanzine.wordpress.com/2017/02/23/attila-the-stockbroker-35-years-a-punk-poet-documentary-and-tour/|title=Attila The Stockbroker \u2013 35 years a punk poet \u2013 documentary and tour|date=23 February 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://experienceguildford.co.uk/news-article.php?eventid=2284|title=Experience Guildford|website=experienceguildford.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Football support==\nBaine is an supporter of [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.]] and for about 16 years was heavily involved in the successful battle to save the club and secure a new stadium, after the [[Goldstone Ground]] was sold to property developers in 1997. The Seagulls finally moved to their new stadium at [[Falmer]] in August 2011. He has been the team's poet in residence since 2000, and was the stadium announcer and DJ for 14 years, first at Gillingham, where the club spent two seasons playing 'home' games, and then at the club's temporary home at [[Withdean Stadium]].  As the main member of the one-off band Seagulls Ska, he had a single reach No. 17 in the [[UK Singles Chart]] in 2005, as part of the campaign for the new stadium.  \"[[Tom Hark (We Want Falmer)]]\".\n\nOn 17 August 2016, just before the start of Brighton's debut in the Premier League, he appeared in a Guardian documentary 'From nowhere to the Premier League' about the fans' role in the club's survival and resurgence<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/video/2017/aug/01/brighton-hove-albion-a-journey-from-nowhere-to-the-premier-league-video|title=Brighton & Hove Albion: a journey from nowhere to the Premier League \u2013 video|first1=Tom|last1=Goudsmit|first2=Ryan|last2=Baxter|date=1 August 2017|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>  On 12 August his poem on that theme, 'From Hereford To Here'<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.bt.com/video/brighton-from-hereford-to-here-91364203272187|title=Brighton: From Hereford to Here|website=BT.com}}</ref> was broadcast by BT Sport immediately before the coverage of their first game against [[Manchester City F.C|Manchester City]]. In 1989 he appeared on the ''Kickback'' segment of ''[[The Channel Four Daily]]'', reflecting on [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]'s 9\u20130 win over [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>Morning Glory: a History of Breakfast Television. Jones, I. Tiverton. Kelly Publishing Ltd. 2004. {{ISBN|1-903053-20-X}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lfchistory.net/viewgame.asp?game_id=1697&season_id=31 |title=Matchdetails from Liverpool - Crystal Palace played on 12 September 1989 - LFChistory - Stats galore for Liverpool FC! |publisher=LFChistory |accessdate=2013-06-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090901170211/http://www.lfchistory.net/viewgame.asp?game_id=1697&season_id=31 |archivedate=1 September 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Poetry collections===\n*''Cautionary tales for Dead Commuters'' (with [[Steven Wells|Seething Wells]]), Allen & Unwin, 1986\n*''Scornflakes'', Bloodaxe, 1992\n*''The Rat-Tailed Maggot & Other Poems'', Roundhead, 1998)\n*''Goldstone Ghosts'', Roundhead, 2001\n*''My Poetic Licence'', Roundhead, 2008\n*''The Long Goodbye (poems for my mother and stepfather)'', Roundhead, 2010\n*''UK Gin Dependence Party and Other Peculiarities'', Roundhead, 2014\n*''Undaunted'', Roundhead, 2017\n\n===Autobiography===\n*''Arguments Yard (35 years of Ranting Verse and Thrash Mandola)'' Cherry Red Books, 2015\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Solo===\n*1981 ''Phasing Out Capitalism'' cassette (No Wonder)\n*1982 ''Rough, Raw and Ranting EP'' with Seething Wells (Radical Wallpaper)\n*1982 ''Cocktails EP'' ([[Cherry Red Records|Cherry Red]])\n*1983 ''Ranting at the Nation'' LP ([[Cherry Red Records|Cherry Red]]) ([[UK Indie Chart|UK Indie]] #12)<ref name=\"Lazell\">{{cite book |last=Lazell |first=Barry |title=Indie Hits 1980-1999 |year= 1997 |publisher=Cherry Red Books |isbn=0-9517206-9-4 }}</ref>\n*1984 ''Sawdust and Empire'' LP (Anagram)\n*1984 ''Radio Rap!'' EP ([[Cherry Red Records|Cherry Red]])\n*1984 ''Livingstone Rap!'' EP (Cherry Red Ken)\n*1987 ''Libyan Students from Hell!'' LP (Plastic Head)\n*1988 ''Scornflakes'' LP/cassette (Probe Plus)\n*1990 (Canada) ''Live at the Rivoli'' LP/cassette (Festival)\n*1991 ''Donkey's Years'' CD/LP/cassette (Musidisc)\n*1991 1991 ''Cheryl - a Rock Opera'' (Strikeback) - with [[John Otway]]\n*1992 (Germany) ''This Is Free Europe'' CD/LP (Terz)\n*1993 (Australia) ''668-Neighbour of the Beast'' CD/cassette (Larrikin)\n*1993 (Germany) ''Live auf St.Pauli'' CD (Terz)\n*1993 ''Attila the Stockbroker's Greatest Hits'' cassette (Roundhead)\n*1999 ''Poems Ancient & Modern'' CD (Roundhead/Mad Butcher)\n*1999 ''The Pen & The Sword'' CD (Roundhead/Mad Butcher)\n*2003 ''Live in Belfast'' (Roundhead)\n*2005 ''Tom Hark (We Want Falmer)'' EP - with Seagulls Ska (Skint)\n*2007 ''Live In Norway'' (Crispin Glover)\n*2008 ''Spirit of the Age'' (Roundhead)\n*2010 ''Disestablished 1980'' (Mad Butcher)\n*2012 \"The Long Goodbye\"/\"Never Too Late\" (Roundhead)\n*2015 \"Live At The Greys\" (Mad Butcher)\n\n===Barnstormer===\n*1995 ''Barnstormer'' cassette (Roundhead Records)\n*1995 (Germany) ''Sarajevo'' EP (Mad Butcher)\n*1996 ''The Siege of Shoreham'' CD/cass (Roundhead Records)\n*1998 ''Live in Hamburg'' cassette (Roundhead Records)\n*1999 (Germany) ''The Siege of Shoreham'' CD (Puffotter Platten) and LP (East Side Records)\n*2000 ''Just One Life'' (Roundhead Records)\n*2004 ''Zero Tolerance'' (Roundhead Records)\n*2004 ''Baghdad Ska'' - split single with Bomb Factory (Repeat Records)\n*2012 ''Bankers & Looters'' CD (Mad Butcher) LP (Hupseeln Records)\n\n===Barnstormer 1649===\n*2018 ''Restoration Tragedy'' double LP and CD (Roundhead Records)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.attilathestockbroker.com}}\n*''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JAaaE8DFX7U 35 Years A Punk Poet]'' (Documentary by Farouq Suleiman)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Attila The Stockbroker}}\n[[Category:20th-century English poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century British poets]]\n[[Category:English singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:English socialists]]\n[[Category:People educated at Christ's Hospital]]\n[[Category:Folk punk musicians]]\n[[Category:English punk rock musicians]]\n[[Category:British mandolinists]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Kent]]\n[[Category:People from Southwick, West Sussex]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brighton and Hove]]\n[[Category:Political music]]\n[[Category:English male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:Cherry Red Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{autobiography|date=September 2018}}\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2018}}\n}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = Attila the Stockbroker\n|image           = Attila The Stockbroker, Calstock 21.jpg\n|caption         = Attila the Stockbroker (centre, playing violin) performing with Barnstormer 1649 at Calstock Hall. September 2018.\n|background      = solo_singer\n|birth_name      = John Baine\n|birth_date      = {{birth date and age|df=y|1957|10|21}}\n|birth_place     = [[Southwick, West Sussex|Southwick]], [[Sussex]], England\n|death_date      = \n|instrument      = [[Singing|Vocals]], [[Mandola]], Violin, Viola, Mandocello,  Recorders, Crumhorn,Rackett,  Cornamuse, Shawm, Rauschpfeife, Bombarde\n|genre           = [[Punk rock]], [[punk poetry]], [[folk punk]], [[Early music]]\n|occupation      = [[Singing|Singer]], [[songwriter]], [[poetry|poet]]\n|years_active    = Late 70s&ndash;present\n|label           = [[Cherry Red Records|Cherry Red]], [[Probe Plus]], Roundhead Records\n|associated_acts = [[Barnstormer 1649]], [[English Disease (band)|English Disease]], [[Brighton Riot Squad]], [[Contingent]], [[John Otway]]\n|website         = [http://www.attilathestockbroker.com attilathestockbroker.com]\n}}\n'''John Baine''' (born 21 October 1957), better known by his stage name '''Attila the Stockbroker''',<ref name=\"Strong\">Strong, Martin C. (2003) ''The Great Indie Discography'', Canongate, {{ISBN|1-84195-335-0}}, p. 208</ref> is a [[Punk literature|punk poet]], multi instrumentalist musician and songwriter. He performs solo and as the leader of the band Barnstormer 1649, who combine early music and punk. He has performed over 3,300 concerts, published eight books of poems and an autobiography (which itself has 38 poems in it) and released over forty recordings (albums and singles).<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguide/comedy/story/0,,1872259,00.html | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=Comedy preview: 16 Sep}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.attilathestockbroker.com/discog.html |title=Discography |publisher=Attila the Stockbroker |date=9 January 2005 |accessdate=2013-06-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526015103/http://www.attilathestockbroker.com/discog.html |archivedate=26 May 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n{{BLP sources section|date=October 2015}}\nBaine attended the [[University of Kent]], Darwin College, in [[Canterbury]] between 1975 and 1978 graduating with a 2:2 degree in French and Politics.<ref name=oxfordref>[http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/oi/authority.20110803095433690 Attila the Stockbroker At Oxford Reference]. Retrieved 5 June 2016</ref> Baine took the performing name Attila the Stockbroker during a short stint as a City stockbroker's clerk between 1980 and 1981 because a colleague accused him of having the eating habits of [[Attila the Hun]].\n\n==Career==\nHaving started performing in the late 1970s after being inspired by the spirit and 'do it yourself' ethos of the [[punk subculture]], particularly [[The Clash]]'s overtly [[Socialism|socialist]] stance, Baine was briefly bass player in punk bands English Disease and Brighton Riot Squad, and spent some time in 1979 in Brussels playing bass in Belgian band Contingent before going solo. (Contingent have now reformed and still gig from time to time)<ref name=\"Strong\" /> He did his first gig as Attila the Stockbroker at Bush Fair Playbarn, [[Harlow, Essex]], on 8 September 1980. At first he performed poems and songs in between bands at [[punk rock]] concerts, accompanying himself on the phased [[electric mandolin]]. After this was smashed over his head by [[Fascism|fascists]] during a fight at a performance in [[North London]] in May 1982, he got a [[mandola]] (a [[Perfect fifth|fifth]] lower) and has played this ever since. He has performed in 24 countries, playing venues ranging from the [[Oxford Union]] in England to [[Squatting|squatted]] punk clubs in Germany, and performs between 80 and 100 shows every year, sometimes more. He toured [[East Germany]] four times before the [[Berlin Wall]] came down, performed in a hotel in [[Enver Hoxha]]'s [[Albania]] and had to turn down the opportunity to perform in North Korea (at the World Festival of Youth & Students in 1989) because he was already booked to tour Canada. He was signed by [[Cherry Red Records|Cherry Red]] in 1982 after recording a session for [[John Peel]]'s [[BBC Radio 1]] show.<ref name=\"Strong\" /> He recorded a second session for Peel in 1983.<ref name=\"KIP\">\"[http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/johnpeel/artists/a/attilathestockbr/ Attila The Stockbroker]\", ''Keeping It Peel'', [[BBC]], retrieved 2010-10-16</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s, he was often the support act for punk bands, including [[The Jam]], [[The Alarm]], [[Newtown Neurotics]], [[New Model Army (band)|New Model Army]] and performed extensively with fellow punk-inspired ranting poets Swift Nick (Nick Swift), Kool Knotes (Richard Edwards), Porky the Poet ([[Phill Jupitus]]) and Seething Wells ([[Steven Wells]]). [[Manic Street Preachers]] supported him at a performance at [[Swansea University]]. In the 1990s, alongside many other things, he toured with [[John Otway]] as Headbutts and Halibuts, and together they wrote a surreal rock opera called ''Cheryl'', a tale of [[Satanism]], [[Trainspotting (hobby)|trainspotting]], drug abuse and unrequited love. He has performed at every [[Glastonbury Festival]] since 1983,at the Edinburgh Fringe on and off for 35 years,  and continues to write topical, satirical material on all kinds of subjects. He puts on an annual beer and music festival 'Glastonwick', currently held at Coombes Farm, near Shoreham though originally in Southwick, his home town nearby. June 2018 saw the 23rd Glastonwick.\n\nNotable works from the 1980s include the poem \"Contributory Negligence\"; various Russian-themed poems, satirizing the alleged [[Cold War]] Russian threat in the context of [[Margaret Thatcher]]'s Britain (such as \"Russians in the [[Department of Health and Social Security|DHSS]]\" and \"Russians in [[McDonald's]]\"). Other political poems include the surreal ''Nigel'' series, such as \"Nigel wants to go to [[C&A]]\". Later pieces include \"Asylum Seeking [[Dalek]]s\", which satirises the [[Right-wing politics|right wing]] press's attitudes to immigration, and \"Hey Celebrity\", which rejects the need for the concept of celebrity.\n\nAttila the Stockbroker formed the band '''Barnstormer''' in 1994, with the initial aim of combining punk rock and early music, which they did to an extent on their debut album ''The Siege of Shoreham'' in 1996. Then Barnstormer's line up changed: they turned into a melodic punk band and for the next 22 years performed regularly across Europe, doing over 500 gigs and releasing three further albums, ''Just One Life'' (2000) ''Zero Tolerance'' (2004) and ''Bankers and Looters'' (2012). In 2018 Attila, who has always been interested in the history of the radical movements spawned in the aftermath of the English Civil War, wrote and recorded an album, ''Restoration Tragedy'' on that theme, combining early music and punk. He changed the name of the band to Barnstormer 1649 (the year of Charles 1st's execution and the  revolutionary uprisings by the [[Levellers]] and [[Diggers]]).\n\n'''Barnstormer 1649''' features Attila on vocals, mandola, violin, viola, crumhorn, cornemuse, shawm, bombarde, rauschpfeife  and recorders; Jason Pegg (formerly of Clearlake) on guitar/backing vocals; M. M. McGhee on drums; Dave Cook (also of Too Many Crooks) on bass/backing vocals and Tim O'Tay on recorders.\n\nAttila now is still doing many solo shows combining his poems and songs. He has released three CDs featuring live recordings of solo gigs: ''Live in Belfast'' (2003) ''Live in Norway'' (2007) and 'Live at the Greys' (2014) His latest book of poems, 'Undaunted' was published in 2017, 'UK Gin Dependence Party and Other Peculiarities' 'in January 2014; ''My Poetic Licence'' came out in 2008. In 2010 he published a pamphlet, ''The Long Goodbye'', containing two poems \u2014 a long one dedicated to and chronicling the life of his mother Muriel, who died in June 2010 after a six-year battle with [[Alzheimer's Disease]], and a shorter one written for his stepfather John Stanford, who died in December 2009. ''The Long Goodbye'' was featured on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Woman's Hour]]'' on Mother's Day 2011.  Attila celebrated 30 years of performing in September 2010 with a 27-date tour of the UK, Germany and the Netherlands. In March 2011 he toured Australia and New Zealand for the first time in ten years, in 2012 made a return to Albania and in February 2014 toured the UK, Germany and Switzerland to promote his latest poetry book. In 2018 he performed at the Limerick Limerick Festival and continues to tour mainland Europe.\n\nOn 8 September 2015, the 35th anniversary of his first gig, it saw the publication of his autobiography, ''Arguments Yard (35 Years of Ranting Verse and Thrash Mandola)'' by Cherry Red Books.\n\nIn September 2016, Baine performed at the Keep Corbyn rally in Brighton in support of [[2016 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|Jeremy Corbyn's campaign]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|Labour Party leadership election]].<ref name=\"doncasterfreepress\">{{cite news |last=Burke|first=Darren|url=https://www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk/news/tv-star-comedians-line-up-for-jeremy-corbyn-rally-in-doncaster-1-8090226|title=TV star comedians line up for Jeremy Corbyn rally in Doncaster|location=Doncaster|newspaper=[[Doncaster Free Press]]|date=26 August 2016|accessdate=1 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 a short documentary ''35 Years A Punk Poet'' about Attila's performance career was produced by film maker Farouq Suleiman.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://repeatfanzine.wordpress.com/2017/02/23/attila-the-stockbroker-35-years-a-punk-poet-documentary-and-tour/|title=Attila The Stockbroker \u2013 35 years a punk poet \u2013 documentary and tour|date=23 February 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://experienceguildford.co.uk/news-article.php?eventid=2284|title=Experience Guildford|website=experienceguildford.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Football support==\nBaine is an supporter of [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.]] and for about 16 years was heavily involved in the successful battle to save the club and secure a new stadium, after the [[Goldstone Ground]] was sold to property developers in 1997. The Seagulls finally moved to their new stadium at [[Falmer]] in August 2011. He has been the team's poet in residence since 2000, and was the stadium announcer and DJ for 14 years, first at Gillingham, where the club spent two seasons playing 'home' games, and then at the club's temporary home at [[Withdean Stadium]].  As the main member of the one-off band Seagulls Ska, he had a single reach No. 17 in the [[UK Singles Chart]] in 2005, as part of the campaign for the new stadium.  \"[[Tom Hark (We Want Falmer)]]\".\n\nOn 17 August 2016, just before the start of Brighton's debut in the Premier League, he appeared in a Guardian documentary 'From nowhere to the Premier League' about the fans' role in the club's survival and resurgence<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/video/2017/aug/01/brighton-hove-albion-a-journey-from-nowhere-to-the-premier-league-video|title=Brighton & Hove Albion: a journey from nowhere to the Premier League \u2013 video|first1=Tom|last1=Goudsmit|first2=Ryan|last2=Baxter|date=1 August 2017|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>  On 12 August his poem on that theme, 'From Hereford To Here'<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.bt.com/video/brighton-from-hereford-to-here-91364203272187|title=Brighton: From Hereford to Here|website=BT.com}}</ref> was broadcast by BT Sport immediately before the coverage of their first game against [[Manchester City F.C|Manchester City]]. In 1989 he appeared on the ''Kickback'' segment of ''[[The Channel Four Daily]]'', reflecting on [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]'s 9-0 win over [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>Morning Glory: a History of Breakfast Television. Jones, I. Tiverton. Kelly Publishing Ltd. 2004. {{ISBN|1-903053-20-X}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lfchistory.net/viewgame.asp?game_id=1697&season_id=31 |title=Matchdetails from Liverpool - Crystal Palace played on 12 September 1989 - LFChistory - Stats galore for Liverpool FC! |publisher=LFChistory |accessdate=2013-06-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090901170211/http://www.lfchistory.net/viewgame.asp?game_id=1697&season_id=31 |archivedate=1 September 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Poetry collections===\n*''Cautionary tales for Dead Commuters'' (with [[Steven Wells|Seething Wells]]), Allen & Unwin, 1986\n*''Scornflakes'', Bloodaxe, 1992\n*''The Rat-Tailed Maggot & Other Poems'', Roundhead, 1998)\n*''Goldstone Ghosts'', Roundhead, 2001\n*''My Poetic Licence'', Roundhead, 2008\n*''The Long Goodbye (poems for my mother and stepfather)'', Roundhead, 2010\n*''UK Gin Dependence Party and Other Peculiarities'', Roundhead, 2014\n*''Undaunted'', Roundhead, 2017\n\n===Autobiography===\n*''Arguments Yard (35 years of Ranting Verse and Thrash Mandola)'' Cherry Red Books, 2015\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Solo===\n*1981 ''Phasing Out Capitalism'' cassette (No Wonder)\n*1982 ''Rough, Raw and Ranting EP'' with Seething Wells (Radical Wallpaper)\n*1982 ''Cocktails EP'' ([[Cherry Red Records|Cherry Red]])\n*1983 ''Ranting at the Nation'' LP ([[Cherry Red Records|Cherry Red]]) ([[UK Indie Chart|UK Indie]] #12)<ref name=\"Lazell\">{{cite book |last=Lazell |first=Barry |title=Indie Hits 1980-1999 |year= 1997 |publisher=Cherry Red Books |isbn=0-9517206-9-4 }}</ref>\n*1984 ''Sawdust and Empire'' LP (Anagram)\n*1984 ''Radio Rap!'' EP ([[Cherry Red Records|Cherry Red]])\n*1984 ''Livingstone Rap!'' EP (Cherry Red Ken)\n*1987 ''Libyan Students from Hell!'' LP (Plastic Head)\n*1988 ''Scornflakes'' LP/cassette (Probe Plus)\n*1990 (Canada) ''Live at the Rivoli'' LP/cassette (Festival)\n*1991 ''Donkey's Years'' CD/LP/cassette (Musidisc)\n*1991 1991 ''Cheryl - a Rock Opera'' (Strikeback) - with [[John Otway]]\n*1992 (Germany) ''This Is Free Europe'' CD/LP (Terz)\n*1993 (Australia) ''668-Neighbour of the Beast'' CD/cassette (Larrikin)\n*1993 (Germany) ''Live auf St.Pauli'' CD (Terz)\n*1993 ''Attila the Stockbroker's Greatest Hits'' cassette (Roundhead)\n*1999 ''Poems Ancient & Modern'' CD (Roundhead/Mad Butcher)\n*1999 ''The Pen & The Sword'' CD (Roundhead/Mad Butcher)\n*2003 ''Live in Belfast'' (Roundhead)\n*2005 ''Tom Hark (We Want Falmer)'' EP - with Seagulls Ska (Skint)\n*2007 ''Live In Norway'' (Crispin Glover)\n*2008 ''Spirit of the Age'' (Roundhead)\n*2010 ''Disestablished 1980'' (Mad Butcher)\n*2012 \"The Long Goodbye\"/\"Never Too Late\" (Roundhead)\n*2015 \"Live At The Greys\" (Mad Butcher)\n\n===Barnstormer===\n*1995 ''Barnstormer'' cassette (Roundhead Records)\n*1995 (Germany) ''Sarajevo'' EP (Mad Butcher)\n*1996 ''The Siege of Shoreham'' CD/cass (Roundhead Records)\n*1998 ''Live in Hamburg'' cassette (Roundhead Records)\n*